bioghist.head: Biographical note
bioghist.p: Samuel MacKay Wilson was born, October 15, 1871, to Mary Bell and Reverend Samuel Ramsay Wilson, in Louisville. His grandfather, Joshua Lacy Wilson and father were Presbyterian ministers. Wilson's primary education was taught by his father before he entered Centre College Academy preparatory school, and then matriculated to a freshman of Centre College as a freshman in 1888. In his junior year, Wilson began teaching and continued to for a few years before returning to Centre College to study law. He apprenticed under Judge Jere R. Morton in Lexington and was admitted to the Fayette County Bar on October 14, 1895. Wilson married Mary Bullock Shelby, the great granddaughter of Kentucky's first governor, Isaac Shelby on October 26, 1899. During the first World War, Wilson served as judge advocate alongside troops in France from 1917-1919. He suffered injury from a fragment air bomb and was discharged with the rank of Lieutenant Colonel. During his career he practiced law alone and in partnerships. His longest lasting partnership was with law associate Mr. Harbison. Notably Wilson aided the United States Supreme Court boundary cases between Missouri and Kansas states. He also defended the constitutionality of Library Laws for small cities throughout Kentucky. Samuel M. Wilson taught law at Transylvania University and was awarded an honorary Doctor of Jurisprudence in 1924. In addition to law, Wilson was very active in civic leadership. He served on the Trustee and Treasurer for Lexington Public Library, and Vice President of Lexington's Chamber of Commerce. He was a member of organizations like the Odd Fellows, Fraternities, American Legion, Reserve Officers mess of Central Kentucky, Pendennis Club Louisville, and many more. He remained active and served as an elder in the Presbyterian Church throughout his life. Wilson was also very interested in regional history and was a member of many historical societies including the Filson Club, Kentucky Historical Society, Mississippi Valley, Ohio Valley, John Bradford Society, National Society of Colonial Wars, Sons of the American Revolution, etc. He died from an infection after surgery at Barnes Hospital in St. Louis on October 10, 1946.

Sources: Obituary for Samuel Wilson (Age 74), Lexington Herald, Lexington, Kentucky, p. 1, October 11, 1946. https://www.newspapers.com/clip/88339096/obituary-for-samuel-m-wilson-aged-74/, accessed 2021 November 4.
Samuel Wilson Named Head of Sesquincentennial Celebration, Courier-Journal, Louisville, p. 6, July 7, 1940, https://www.newspapers.com/clip/88339560/, accessed 2021 November 4.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Samuel M. Wilson Classified Papers (dated 1748-1973, undated; 34 cubic feet; 72 boxes) are part of Judge Samuel M. Wilson's papers and contain legal court records and history subject files. The classified files include such items as legal papers, law suits, bank notes, church papers, correspondence, addresses, notes on Wilson's research projects, articles, genealogies of many Kentucky families, and materials concerning associations, organizations and Kentucky history. Some of the topics covered in detail include the American Legion, the American Bar Association, Burley Tobacco Growers' Cooperative Association, the Filson Club, the YMCA, Mammoth Cave, the Henry Clay Memorial Foundation, Genet Mission, Kappa Alpha, the Kentucky constitution, the Kentucky Governor's Advisory Council, Kentucky Bar Association, Kentucky Union Company, Transylvania Company, Wilson family genealogy, Woodrow Wilson, Joseph H. Daviess, Henry Clay, Andrew Jackson, and Isaac Shelby.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: The physical rights to the materials in this collection are held by the University of Kentucky Special Collections Research Center.
